reviewText:
Early Access Review

If you are looking for a casual game development entertainment, look no further, as Game Corp DX will provide you the ability to create games, without complex micromanagement that would consume so much of your time, thus allowing you to pump out games and win some neat awards, while keeping a funny gaming enviroment.

Players are artists who create their own reality within the game.

Shigeru Miyamoto

Without any further delay, I present to you my review of Game Corp DX.

GameplayIf this is the first time you’re reading one of my reviews, I’ll let you know a little secret - I’m completely and utterly addicted to management games, so I couldn’t avoid not taking a look at Game Corp DX (GCDX).
For those familiar with the growing Game Dev sub-genre, you’ll find that GCDX isn’t nearly as complex as the rest. In fact, it’s incredibly simple, and your general aim is to win every award, or at least some, at the award ceremony, which happens once a year. As you’d expect, you start with a little room, in which you have to hire some folks to help you start your wannabe award winning studios. After you’ve fully expanded, which consists of hiring everyone in the city, you’ll be offered the opportunity to relocate your studio to another city. Luckily enough, the room stays the same, as well as all the furniture. The changes are noticed on the exterior, and the ability to expand your walls, allowing you to buy more workstations, and therefore expand your team. You’ll also have to train your little minions, or else you’ll be stuck watching every other studio win an award, while you fight to survive.
There’s no real challenge to the game, as you’ll most likely always make a profit with every game. That said, it’s more of a casual game, with a pretty active developer that’s constantly participating on the forums, listening to suggestions and trying to solve any possible bugs.
The tutorial is also pretty helpful, as it’s supposed to be, and after it’s done, to offer some sense of continuity to the player, there are a number of objectives to reach which will reward the player with some money.
All of this is completed with a very comical and funny graphical style, which I enjoyed quite a bit. Although the same can’t be said for the music, which gets somewhat annoying after a while.


Pros Thorough tutorial;
Comical graphical setting;
Wide variety of NPCs;
Diversified critics;
Enjoyable gameplay;
Requirements for each skill are shown during game creation;
Price;
The developer is quite active on his forums.
Considering it's an Early Access (EA) game, I've decided to add a Neutral" category

